WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hi, my name is Michael Chow, and thanks for watching this RStudioConf talk.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:15.000
I'll be going through Siuba, which is a port of dplyr to Python.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Since you're watching RStudioConf, I'm guessing that you're on board with R and dplyr for data analysis.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.000
And I've got to say I love R, but I also love Python.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:30.000
And depending on the project or task, I've often found myself having to switch between R and Python,

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
or sort of juggle both at the same time.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:39.000
And I'm guessing this isn't a super unusual experience, since Python's just incredibly popular.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:45.000
If you look at stack overflow posts, the sort of predominant tool in Python for data analysis, pandas,

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
counts for about 3% of posts a month.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:51.000
That's just an incredible amount.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:56.000
And so a lot of my interactions have been with people who use pandas for data analysis.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
But as time has gone on, I've found myself reaching more and more for dplyr,

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
and I've really thought a lot about that and tried to figure out what's going on there.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And to kind of set the stage, I thought I'd just use a dumb analogy,

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
that pandas is a lot maybe like a double-decker bus.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:19.000
So this is in Hong Kong, and this thing's really built for carrying capacity.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
If you have to ship like 80 humans somewhere, this is your tool.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
You stack them on top of each other, you're golden.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
The challenge is that it's kind of cumbersome.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
It can't go everywhere. It's probably scary to back up.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:42.000
And in contrast, in Hong Kong, there's another vehicle, the minibus, or suba, that's the opposite approach.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:47.000
So tiny capacity, holds like 16 people, and it's just a terror on wheels.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.000
So the BBC describes it as Hong Kong's wildest ride.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:56.000
And these things are just fast, they can go anywhere, and they can sort of get you.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
They're super flexible.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.000
So I kind of think that that really reminds me of dplyr,

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
that dplyr is incredible for exploratory analysis.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
It can just get you to where you want to go quickly.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:17.000
Pandas is great at computation, but can be a little bit cumbersome, sort of on the fly.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:24.000
So suba aims to be small but mighty by leveraging dplyr-like syntax in Python,

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:29.000
but doing computation behind the scenes in pandas or SQL.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And I've tried to live code with suba just to sort of battle test it and make sure it's ready for the big time.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:41.000
I think a big question is what dplyr is really doing that's so useful.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:47.000
And to really understand, we have to go back to Hadley's 2014 talk where he introduced dplyr.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
And he mentions that analysts sort of have two bottlenecks,

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.000
a cognitive bottleneck and a computational bottleneck.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.000
The computational one's the one we think of most often,

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
which is as the data becomes bigger, it takes longer to run the code.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.000
But intriguingly, Hadley mentions he thinks a lot about the cognitive bottleneck,

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:13.000
which is how should we think about the data and describe what we want to do to the data or code.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:19.000
And dplyr aims at this cognitive bottleneck to help people sort of focus their thoughts

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:22.000
and to give people strategies for data analysis.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:29.000
It does this by kind of slimming down, taking this big space and slimming down the options that people have.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:32.000
So there are five simple verbs.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And all of these critically can combine with an operator group by.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
All of these take a data frame and return a data frame.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.000
And he mentions that overall, it's a very constrained design,

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
especially compared to his previous tool, Plyar.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:55.000
So Subha aims to sort of let people capture those dplyr-like thoughts and keep them

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:02.000
while writing dplyr syntax in Python and then doing the computation in Pandas.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So the gist is Subha lets you transfer your thoughts from R to Python.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:19.000
All right, so I'm going to try to show three motivating cases where it can be tricky to transfer dplyr thoughts to Pandas.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Three roadblocks that people hit.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:25.000
And I know it's tempting to see dplyr in Pandas. It's pretty similar.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
So in this example, they're doing roughly the same thing.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
And they're using basically the same code.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.000
So it's a group summarize.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
We're calculating the average of a column.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.000
And we're renaming the result average HP.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
And we get roughly the same output.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.000
But it's also worth noting, if you take this somewhere like Twitter or look around,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.000
you'll see some pretty scathing reviews.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.000
So dplyr has forever ruined Pandas for me.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:58.000
Or Chelsea notes, every picture shows Pandas in chaos.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.000
And I think it's worth noting these people, I think they like Pandas.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.000
So this isn't a straight critique of Pandas.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:12.000
But it can be really frustrating when you try to go from one tool and the way it structures thinking to another.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:18.000
And so I would say these three cases try to bring that to the surface, what's going on.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.000
The first roadblock is select.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.000
So select is really a very basic action.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
You can choose columns.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:26.000
You can drop columns.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.000
You might match certain columns or rename a column.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:34.000
And the trick is that Pandas uses different names for all these actions.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:38.000
So there are four different methods, one for each action.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.000
The other thing is that sometimes they have kind of funky arguments you need to pass.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:47.000
So you might have to say axis equals one to say, oh, I want to do this to the columns.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Or you might have to say columns equals.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
Those are kind of different ways of saying the same thing.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:59.000
The last is that sometimes you have to use sort of intense programming constructs, like a lambda function,

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:03.000
if you want to do things like match on a string.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:08.000
In contrast, dplyr uses the same verb for all these actions, select.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
And it's really easy to change between what you're doing,

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:18.000
to go from keeping a column to dropping a column, or even to combine these actions together.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:24.000
And so this is a case, I think, of where sort of changing what you do requires changing gears, right,

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:29.000
and shifting between these different functions and methods in Pandas.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:33.000
The second example is, I would say, groupby.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:39.000
And this is really, I would say grouping is really a critical activity in data analysis in dplyr.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:45.000
And the Pandas docs describe some translations from R to Pandas.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:48.000
And it looks pretty straightforward, at least for these cases.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:56.000
But actually, I would say groupby in dplyr and Pandas use radically different underlying grammars.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:03.000
So in this example, on the left, I'm showing a filter in Pandas or a mutate.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
And note there are two ways of doing it, or multiple ways, I should say.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
So you can use query, that's the top left, or eval on the top right,

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:17.000
or an alternative way to filter on the bottom left is these blocks,

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.000
or to mutate a sign on the bottom right.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:29.000
Critically, we can ask, what happens when we try to groupby before these operations?

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:33.000
And the answer is that none of them work.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:39.000
And the trick is a groupdata in Pandas, a dataframe groupby,

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:45.000
actually doesn't have even any of these methods on it to perform these operations,

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:50.000
except in one case where the operation just sort of fails.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:54.000
And this is probably really surprising, I think, for dplyr users.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:01.000
The trick ends up being you have to shift the groupby from outside of the verb to inside it.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:06.000
So you basically have to move groupby into your column operations.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
And again, this isn't necessarily bad,

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
and it means Pandas can still do the same computations as dplyr.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:15.000
It's just, I think, surprising for dplyr users,

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:20.000
and for me challenging to do when I'm trying to analyze data quickly.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
The third roadblock, I'd say, is SQL.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:28.000
So dplyr users, if you're like me, working in industry,

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
I lean on dplyr and dbplyr being able to generate SQL heavily.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.000
So you can just swap out your data source to SQL,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:39.000
and dplyr will generate a SQL query for you.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:44.000
In contrast, if you're using Pandas, you just need to switch to writing SQL.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:49.000
And that's what I see happen quite a bit in industry is once it hits the database,

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:51.000
people just switch and start coding SQL.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:57.000
So your computation changes, and how you code ends up changing as a result.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.000
So to recap, dplyr is really powerful.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:07.000
It uses one verb, select, for all the cases for grabbing columns.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:12.000
For groupby, you have this sort of really nice expressive syntax

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
where you can modify the full table action.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:21.000
So you can have a grouped mutate or a grouped filter or group summarize.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.000
In contrast, Pandas is computationally powerful,

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.000
and it's packed with options.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.000
But that means that you might have to do a little bit more work up front

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
during the analysis.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
And this makes it great for engineering,

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.000
but maybe a big challenge, I think, for exploratory data analysis

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
or quick analyses.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
All right, so we looked at some core challenges

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.000
in translating dplyr thoughts about data analysis to Pandas.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:50.000
Now I'm going to switch gears and look how Suba can help you

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:54.000
basically preserve those thoughts and code them in Python.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And it aims to do this as faithfully to dplyr as possible.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:02.000
So I'm going to show you an example of going from dplyr code to Suba.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
I apologize.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:07.000
I know I start with these parentheses and put the pipe

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:11.000
at the beginning of the line, and some people hate that.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:14.000
Sorry, my bad.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
So let's go ahead and just start the switch.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
First, we'll change our imports.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
So rather than using library, we'll do our Python imports.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:29.000
Then we'll change the pipe to be greater than, greater than.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Next, we'll put an underscore dot in front of the variable names.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:40.000
And this sort of has to happen in order for it to be Python syntax.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.000
And then the last thing is a little bit tricky.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
We're going to take this mean function call,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
and we're going to change it to a method

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:53.000
so it's more similar to how Pandas expresses operations.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:57.000
All right, and so in a sense, with these few simple changes,

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:04.000
we've gone from dplyr in R to Suba in Python.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
So in looking side by side,

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:09.000
hopefully my goal is that you can kind of like squint your eyes

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:12.000
and they just look like the same code, right,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
and you can just figure out how to swap between them.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
So now I want to go through the three examples that I showed before

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
and just give you a sense for what they look like in Suba.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
So the first roadblock was select,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:30.000
and now looking back at this example with Suba on the left,

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.000
it should be basically the same thing.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:38.000
Now you just have underscore dot before the variable names.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
It's worth noting, too, the very bottom one

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
where you select certain columns, it's really easy to do,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
and it matches up sort of with the Pandas code.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:51.000
So Pandas, you can do this dot str dot ends with,

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:56.000
and it will return true whenever a column matches that,

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.000
and Suba just lines up with that way of doing things,

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:04.000
so it corresponds to the Pandas way.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
The second example is groupby.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:11.000
So we showed a few different ways of doing filter and mutate.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:16.000
So the filter and mutate now for Pandas are on the right,

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
and let's show how Suba does it.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:23.000
So here's the Suba filter and mutate on the left.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:27.000
Notice that they're eerily similar, hopefully, to dplyr,

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:33.000
and we can just tuck in the groupby above the filter and mutate

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
to make it a grouped filter or a grouped mutate.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:40.000
So it's meant to be easy to just swap in and out.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
The last example was SQL.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:47.000
So I think this is kind of the biggest, most useful part of Suba

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:51.000
is you can swap out your data source from being a Pandas data frame

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:56.000
to a SQLAlchemy, essentially a SQLAlchemy connection,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
and Suba will generate the SQL query

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:04.000
or run the query and return a table of data, just like dplyr.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:09.000
And right now it's mostly Postgres and Redshift that I've worked on supporting,

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
but it can be extended to more backends.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:15.000
So there's early support for MySQL and SQLite,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
and I'm hoping to build those out further.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:22.000
I think one of the incredible things is that you get ggplot for free,

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
and that's not by any of my work,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.000
but by the work of a person named Hassan,

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
who built a package called plot9,

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:35.000
which is an incredibly faithful port of ggplot.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:41.000
So ideally you can just do the full data transformation,

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:45.000
data visualization, and you can carry over your hard-earned skills

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.000
from R to Python.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:54.000
So just to recap, Suba tries to use a very similar syntax to dplyr.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:58.000
There are some cases where it needed to be tweaked a little bit

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.000
to be Pythonic or to just be Python syntax.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And incredibly, it aims to bring you SQL and ggplot.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And I found that these things really helped me get back up to speed

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:16.000
in data analysis, and have been fun just to carry into Python

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
and to discuss with people.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.000
All right, so we talked about three roadblocks you might face

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:26.000
when translating dplyr code and dots to pandas,

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:29.000
and how Suba lets you sort of roll past those

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:34.000
by essentially copying and pasting dplyr into Python.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
Now I want to zoom out a little bit and ask,

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:39.000
why is Suba worth it in the long term?

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
Why should you try out or adopt Suba?

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:46.000
And the first thing I want to harken back to is Hadley's point in 2014

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
about cognition and computation,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:54.000
that dplyr as a cognitive tool has, if you've used it over the long term,

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:01.000
probably really helped you build skills to ask important questions of your data.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:05.000
And those skills aren't even maybe that related to programming.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:10.000
So why not just bring those skills with you into Python?

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:14.000
The next point is Suba uses dplyr's architecture,

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:18.000
and this lets it very flexibly add new backends.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:23.000
So whether you run against SQL or pandas, Suba can support it.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:29.000
And I'm hoping to extend support to Python-specific tools in the future, like Dask,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:33.000
and tools like Spark, as well as fleshing out MySQL support.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:39.000
The next thing is that Suba runs just an enormous glut of continuous integration tests.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:42.000
So it's incredibly thoroughly tested.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:46.000
I would say it's like paranoid about ensuring that you get the same result back,

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
whether you're running on SQL or pandas.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And every time I push code, it runs thousands of tests.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:58.000
The last thing is developer docs.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
So I've tried to leave a nice trail of breadcrumbs.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:08.000
So if you're curious about the internal workings of Suba or looking to patch or extend it,

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
there are just enormous resources to do that.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
I'd suggest the programming guide in the Suba docs,

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
which goes through all of Suba's parts.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:25.000
Or I have something called architectural decision records in GitHub that document key decisions I made,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:31.000
why they were made, and contain sketches of those decisions.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:37.000
The last thing is if you're interested in learning Suba, there are some nice alleys you can go down.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:42.000
So the first thing I'd recommend is Dave Robinson's TidyTuesday screencasts.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:45.000
These are actually in R, so maybe not as related,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:51.000
but they were an incredible resource when developing Suba and actually a big motivation to work on it.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:59.000
I think being able to see a person move quickly through data analyses in a holistic setting is really important.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:07.000
And TidyTuesday is a project that releases new data every week, lets you sort of see things in action.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:12.000
The other thing is there's an interactive tutorial for Suba on learn.suba.org.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:17.000
So if you're curious to just get started, even if you've never coded before,

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:21.000
the tutorial's made to make it easy to get started.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.000
It's something I've tested on my family and friends,

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:28.000
and I'm really excited for the opportunity for Suba to make it really easy for learners

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:33.000
to take their first steps into coding and data analysis.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:40.000
The last thing is that I've tried to put up live analyses on YouTube of analyzing data for an hour,

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:45.000
whether it's translating Dave's analyses from R into Suba, Python,

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:50.000
or doing TidyTuesday data analyses for an hour.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
So I highly recommend watching those if you want to see Suba in action,

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
and then trying Suba out on TidyTuesday.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:01.000
Just take it for a spin and see what it looks like

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:06.000
and how it compares, say, to using R or another Python tool.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:12.000
So just to recap, you can find Suba on GitHub at mhau.suba.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
You can pip install it.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:19.000
I can't highly recommend TidyTuesday enough.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:25.000
It'll let you get a feel for what data analysis with Suba looks like.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:27.000
And there's learn.suba.org.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:32.000
If you've never coded, I've tried to design this for you,

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:39.000
and I'd love to see people take their first steps into data analysis through this course.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:43.000
So thanks to everybody who helped contribute to Suba.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:46.000
Thanks to RStudio for putting this together.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.000
And thanks to the army of people who gave feedback on this talk

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:53.000
and made it much, much better than its first version.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.000
So thanks for watching.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:57.000
I hope you'll try Suba out.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:01.000
And if you have any questions, please feel free to reach out to me on GitHub

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.000
or on Twitter at chowthedoc.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:05.000
Thanks.

